<body>
    <h1>Fibonacci Spiral Debug: Common Implementation Errors</h1>
    <p>This page illustrates how incorrect base cases in a Fibonacci sequence implementation can lead to a "buggy" looking spiral, often mistaken for a canvas rendering issue.</p>
    <p>The canvas API itself is generally robust for drawing arcs and lines. The "bug" is almost always in the logic that calculates the dimensions or positions.</p>

    <div class="container">
        <div class="canvas-wrapper">
            <h2>Buggy Fibonacci Spiral (Incorrect Base Cases)</h2>
            <canvas id="buggyCanvas" width="400" height="400"></canvas>
            <p>
                This spiral uses a Fibonacci sequence generated with incorrect base cases (e.g., `[0, 1]` or `[1, 1]` for the first two numbers, but then the spiral logic starts from an index that doesn't align with the visual representation of the spiral's growth).
                The visual result is a spiral that doesn't "fit" correctly or has unexpected gaps/overlaps, especially at the beginning.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="canvas-wrapper">
            <h2>Corrected Fibonacci Spiral (Proper Base Cases)</h2>
            <canvas id="correctedCanvas" width="400" height="400"></canvas>
            <p>
                This spiral uses a Fibonacci sequence generated with appropriate base cases and a drawing logic that correctly maps the sequence to the geometric construction of the spiral.
                Notice how the arcs connect smoothly and progressively, forming the expected golden spiral shape.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2>Explanation of the Common Bug</h2>
    <p>
        A common pitfall in implementing Fibonacci spirals is how the initial Fibonacci numbers are generated and then used to define the square sizes for the spiral.
        The classical Fibonacci sequence starts `0, 1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, ...`.
        When constructing a spiral, we often start with squares of side lengths 1 and 1, then 2, then 3, and so on.
        If the Fibonacci sequence generation or its indexing for drawing is off, the initial squares (and thus the first arcs) will be incorrectly sized or positioned.
    </p>
    <p>
        For instance, if `fib(0)` is 0 and `fib(1)` is 1, but the drawing logic expects the first two "unit" squares to be `fib(1)` and `fib(2)` (both 1), then using `fib(0)` and `fib(1)` for initial squares would be incorrect.
        The "buggy" example below might generate `[0, 1, 1, 2, ...]` but then attempts to use `fib[0]` and `fib[1]` for the initial squares, leading to an initial square of size 0, which is problematic, or it might skip a crucial `1` unit square.
    </p>
    <p>
        The corrected version ensures that the sequence used for square sizes directly maps to the `1, 1, 2, 3, 5, ...` progression that forms the visual spiral.
    </p>

    <h2>Fibonacci Sequence Code Comparison</h2>
    <h3>Buggy Fibonacci Function (Example of a common misstep)</h3>
    <pre><code>
function getBuggyFibonacciSequence(n) {
    const sequence = [0, 1]; // Starts with 0, 1
    for (let i = 2; i <= n; i++) {
        sequence.push(sequence[i - 1] + sequence[i - 2]);
    }
    return sequence;
}
// If drawing starts from index 0 or 1, it might not align with the visual 1,1,2,3... progression.
// E.g., if we try to make a square of size sequence[0] (0), or miss the initial '1' unit square.
    </code></pre>

    <h3>Corrected Fibonacci Function</h3>
    <pre><code>
function getCorrectedFibonacciSequence(n) {
    const sequence = [1, 1]; // Starts with 1, 1 for the first two squares
    for (let i = 2; i < n; i++) { // Note: iterate up to n-1 to get n numbers
        sequence.push(sequence[i - 1] + sequence[i - 2]);
    }
    return sequence;
}
// This sequence [1, 1, 2, 3, 5, ...] directly maps to the sizes of squares needed for the spiral.
    </code></pre>

    <script>
        // --- Fibonacci Sequence Generators ---

        // Buggy version: Starts with 0, 1. If the drawing logic then tries to use fib[0] (0) or misaligns
        // with the visual requirement of initial 1x1 squares, it will look wrong.
        function getBuggyFibonacciSequence(n) {
            const sequence = [0, 1]; // Common mathematical start, but problematic for spiral geometry if misused
            for (let i = 2; i < n; i++) {
                sequence.push(sequence[i - 1] + sequence[i - 2]);
            }
            return sequence;
        }

        // Corrected version: Starts with 1, 1. This directly corresponds to the first two unit squares
        // in the geometric construction of the Fibonacci spiral.
        function getCorrectedFibonacciSequence(n) {
            if (n === 0) return [];
            if (n === 1) return [1];
            const sequence = [1, 1];
            for (let i = 2; i < n; i++) {
                sequence.push(sequence[i - 1] + sequence[i - 2]);
            }
            return sequence;
        }

        // --- Drawing Function ---
        function drawFibonacciSpiral(canvasId, fibSequenceGenerator, numSegments, scaleFactor = 10) {
            const canvas = document.getElementById(canvasId);
            const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');
            ctx.clearRect(0, 0, canvas.width, canvas.height); // Clear previous drawings

            const fib = fibSequenceGenerator(numSegments + 2); // Get enough numbers for the spiral
            if (fib.length < 2) return; // Not enough numbers to draw a spiral

            // Center the spiral roughly
            let currentX = canvas.width / 2;
            let currentY = canvas.height / 2;

            ctx.strokeStyle = '#007bff';
            ctx.lineWidth = 2;

            let direction = 0; // 0: right, 1: down, 2: left, 3: up
            let offsetX = 0;
            let offsetY = 0;

            // Adjust initial position based on the first two squares to make it somewhat centered
            // This adjustment is crucial and often where bugs appear.
            // For the corrected spiral, we start with 1x1 squares.
            // For the buggy spiral, if fib[0] is 0, this will cause issues.
            if (canvasId === 'correctedCanvas') {
                // For corrected, we start with 1x1, so adjust to roughly center the whole thing
                currentX -= (fib[numSegments - 1] * scaleFactor) / 2;
                currentY -= (fib[numSegments - 1] * scaleFactor) / 2;
                // A more precise initial offset for the corrected spiral
                currentX += fib[0] * scaleFactor; // Move right by first square
                currentY -= fib[numSegments - 2] * scaleFactor; // Move up by the last square
            } else { // Buggy canvas, just try to center based on the largest possible square
                currentX -= (fib[numSegments - 1] * scaleFactor) / 2;
                currentY -= (fib[numSegments - 1] * scaleFactor) / 2;
            }


            ctx.beginPath();
            let startAngle, endAngle;

            for (let i = 0; i < numSegments; i++) {
                // The actual number to use for the square side.
                // For the 'buggy' one, if fib[0] is 0, this will be 0, causing problems.
                // For the 'corrected' one, fib[i] will be 1, 1, 2, 3...
                const sideLength = fib[i] * scaleFactor;

                // Skip drawing if sideLength is 0 (can happen with buggy fib[0])
                if (sideLength <= 0) {
                    // It's important to understand that a 0-length square or arc won't be visible
                    // but it can mess up subsequent calculations if not handled.
                    // For the purpose of demonstration, we'll continue, but it illustrates a problem.
                    continue;
                }

                ctx.save();
                ctx.strokeStyle = 'rgba(0, 123, 255, 0.5)'; // Lighter for arcs
                ctx.lineWidth = 1;
                // Draw the square for visual debugging
                ctx.strokeRect(currentX + offsetX, currentY + offsetY, sideLength, sideLength);
                ctx.restore();

                ctx.strokeStyle = '#dc3545'; // Red for the spiral itself
                ctx.lineWidth = 2;

                // Calculate arc parameters based on current square and direction
                let arcX, arcY, radius;

                switch (direction) {
                    case 0: // Right (draws arc from bottom-left corner of the square)
                        arcX = currentX + offsetX + sideLength;
                        arcY = currentY + offsetY + sideLength;
                        radius = sideLength;
                        startAngle = Math.PI;
                        endAngle = Math.PI * 1.5;
                        // Move for next square
                        offsetX += sideLength;
                        break;
                    case 1: // Down (draws arc from top-left corner of the square)
                        arcX = currentX + offsetX;
                        arcY = currentY + offsetY + sideLength;
                        radius = sideLength;
                        startAngle = Math.PI * 1.5;
                        endAngle = Math.PI * 2;
                        // Move for next square
                        offsetY += sideLength;
                        break;
                    case 2: // Left (draws arc from top-right corner of the square)
                        arcX = currentX + offsetX;
                        arcY = currentY + offsetY;
                        radius = sideLength;
                        startAngle = 0;
                        endAngle = Math.PI * 0.5;
                        // Move for next square
                        offsetX -= sideLength;
                        break;
                    case 3: // Up (draws arc from bottom-right corner of the square)
                        arcX = currentX + offsetX + sideLength;
                        arcY = currentY + offsetY;
                        radius = sideLength;
                        startAngle = Math.PI * 0.5;
                        endAngle = Math.PI;
                        // Move for next square
                        offsetY -= sideLength;
                        break;
                }

                // Only draw an arc if radius is positive
                if (radius > 0) {
                    ctx.arc(arcX, arcY, radius, startAngle, endAngle, false);
                }

                // Update direction for the next segment
                direction = (direction + 1) % 4;
            }
            ctx.stroke();
        }

        // --- Initialize Spirals ---
        const numSegments = 10; // Number of Fibonacci numbers to use for segments
        const scale = 10;       // Scale factor to make the spiral visible

        // Draw the buggy spiral
        drawFibonacciSpiral('buggyCanvas', getBuggyFibonacciSequence, numSegments, scale);

        // Draw the corrected spiral
        drawFibonacciSpiral('correctedCanvas', getCorrectedFibonacciSequence, numSegments, scale);

    </script>
</body>
</html>
